# mJig Project Conventions

## Documentation Sync (Mandatory)

When modifying mJig source files, also update `AGENTS.md` and `README.md` to reflect:
- New or modified parameters
- New or renamed functions
- New files added to the `Private/` tree
- New features, behaviors, theme colors, UI components
- Changes to hotkeys or interactive controls
- New gotchas or patterns discovered during development

## AGENTS.md is the Source of Truth

`AGENTS.md` lives at the **project root** (`c:\Projects\mJig\AGENTS.md`). Every change to the codebase must be cross-checked against `AGENTS.md` for accuracy. Before finishing any task:
1. Re-read the relevant sections of `AGENTS.md` to confirm they still match the code
2. Update any sections that have become stale due to your changes
3. If you added a new pattern, gotcha, or architectural concept, add it to the appropriate section

Never reference `AGENTS.md` at any other path (e.g. `resources/AGENTS.md` is stale — it was moved to root).

## Maintain `.cursor/rules/` Alongside `AGENTS.md`

The `.cursor/rules/*.mdc` files are distilled from `AGENTS.md` for fast AI context loading. When you update `AGENTS.md`, also update the relevant `.cursor/rules/` file(s) to stay in sync:
- New rendering patterns or invariants -> `tui-rendering.mdc`
- New PowerShell gotchas or collection rules -> `powershell-patterns.mdc`
- New IPC protocol changes or epoch guard updates -> `ipc-patterns.mdc`
- New dialog structure patterns -> `dialog-patterns.mdc`
- New P/Invoke types or API gotchas -> `pinvoke-patterns.mdc`
- New theme colors or notification changes -> `theme-and-notifications.mdc`
- New resize handling patterns -> `resize-handling.mdc`
- New project-wide conventions -> `project-conventions.mdc` (this file)

If a change doesn't fit an existing rule file, create a new focused `.mdc` file with the appropriate `globs` scope.
- New naming, terminology, or comment conventions -> `naming-standards.mdc`

## File Placement Rule

All new functions go in their own `.ps1` file under the appropriate `Private/` subdirectory and are dot-sourced in `Start-mJig.psm1`. Never inline new functions into the main `.psm1`.

After adding new files:
1. Add `. "$PSScriptRoot\Private\...\NewFunction.ps1"` in the appropriate section of `Start-mJig.psm1`
2. Update `AGENTS.md` (Code Structure Map + Quick Reference table)
3. Ensure `Build/Build-Module.ps1` picks up the new file

## Commit Workflow

When the user says they are ready to commit:
1. Run `git status` and `git log --oneline -5`
2. Write commit message: first line = concise summary of biggest changes. Body = bulleted key changes. End with "See CHANGELOG.md for full details."
3. Write message to `_commit_msg.txt`, run `git commit -F _commit_msg.txt`, then delete the temp file (PowerShell does not support heredoc in git commands)
4. Verify with `git status` that the working tree is clean
5. **After commit**: move current `[Latest] - Unreleased` content into a versioned section with commit hash and today's date. Replace with fresh empty `[Latest] - Unreleased`. Do NOT stage or commit this changelog prep.

## Comment Style

Comments state **what** a block is for in one line. Detailed context belongs in `AGENTS.md`, not inline. No contractions, no editorial notes, no historical version notes. See `naming-standards.mdc` for the full rule set.

## Temporary Test Scripts

Place throwaway `.ps1` test scripts in `resources/` (git-ignored). Never in the project root. The `_diag/` folder is for runtime diagnostic output only, not agent-authored test scripts.
